    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1566374652,
    "creation_date" : 1566374652,
    "answer_id" : 57587057,
    "question_id" : 1456566,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>The below code snippet will help evaluate primitive type holding NaN.</p>\n\n<p><code>double dbl = Double.NaN;\nDouble.valueOf(dbl).isNaN() ? true : false;</code></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 19593935,
      "reputation" : 11,
      "user_id" : 14340388,
      "user_type" : "unregistered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2354a4c591ce5943326ea6b6afbbb87b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "PeterPainter",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/14340388/peterpainter"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1601053959,
    "last_edit_date" : 1601053959,
    "creation_date" : 1601039106,
    "answer_id" : 64064755,
    "question_id" : 1456566,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If your value under test is a <em>Double</em> (not a primitive) and might be <code>null</code> (which is obviously not a number too), then you should use the following term:</p>\n<p><code>(value==null || Double.isNaN(value))</code></p>\n<p>Since <code>isNaN()</code> wants a primitive (rather than boxing any primitive double to a <em>Double</em>), passing a <code>null</code> value (which can't be unboxed to a <em>Double</em>) will result in an exception instead of the expected <code>false</code>.</p>\n"
  } ],
